{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492984"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1197"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1197"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.04,0.02,0.07,0.59]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47470"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1197"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32186"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1310"},{"type":"tags","id":"2968"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8182"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3543"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12266"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47470"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with bilateral breast tenderness and heaviness. The symptoms have been present intermittently over six months, starting in the week prior to menstruation and easing with the onset of menses. At times the discomfort can radiate to her armpits. She has tried nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and paracetamol with little benefit. No abnormalities are identified on examination or ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is an evidence-based measure that most alleviates breast pain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Evening primrose oil","Cessation of coffee drinking","Treatment with flucloxacillin","Vitamin E supplementation","Ensuring patient is wearing a well-fitted bra"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe woman in the stem above presents with persistent breast tenderness for a six-month duration. The pain she experiences is cyclical in nature which coincides with her menstrual cycle, alluding to a diagnosis of cyclical mastalgia. This condition is common, affecting up to 70% of women at some stage in their lives. It is typically benign and self-limited in nature but approximately 15% of women will require some form of treatment. Despite its benign and typically self-limiting nature, cyclical mastalgia is an important differential to keep in mind. The cyclical pain is associated with hormonal fluctuations throughout the menstrual cycle and usually presents in the week preceding the onset of menses. The pain is frequently bilateral and most severe in the upper outer quadrant of the breasts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment for cyclical mastalgia is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst-line therapy for cyclical breast pain involves conservative measures including reassurance, breast support (i.e., a well-fitting bra), and simple analgesia like nonsteroidal anti-inflammatories (i.e., paracetamol or additional NSAIDs). Topical NSAIDs can also be used (i.e., diclofenac gel).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESecond-line therapy for cyclical mastalgia is indicated with consistent pain for six months despite adequate first-line therapy. Options include tamoxifen and danazol however there are significant adverse effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExplanation and reassurance play a vital role in treating mastalgia and may be sufficient for some patients. Conservative measures include \u003Cstrong\u003Ewearing a well-fitting bra\u003C/strong\u003E and by correcting this, many studies have shown that symptoms may be completely alleviated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESupplementation, such as \u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin E\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eevening primrose oil\u003C/strong\u003E, is used due to anecdotal success in some women. These interventions are not supported by current evidence and are not recommended as first or second-line therapies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaffeine intake\u003C/strong\u003E, iodine deficiency, and dietary fat intake have not been definitively established as causal factors in mastalgia, and dietary modifications are not effective treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreat with flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be recommended if the patient had mastitis. However, the fact that this is bilateral, and the timeline and cyclical nature of the pain for this patient is much more likely to be due to cyclical mastalgia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA management algorithm can be found in the article \u003Cem\u003ECurrent Management and Treatment Options for Breast Pain by Cornell, et al. (2020)\u003C/em\u003E [reference 3].\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-line therapy for cyclical mastalgia pain includes conservative measures including reassurance, physical aids (clothing, etc), and simple analgesia.","Second-line therapies for cyclical mastalgia may be required in patients who continue to have severe breast pain for six months despite first-line therapy.","Medications used to treat mastalgia have significant side effects and their use needs to be strictly monitored by a GP or in consultation with a specialist."],"references":["Golshan, M, Breast pain [Internet]. Uptodate.com. 2021 [cited 18 August 2021]. Available from: \u003C https://www.uptodate.com/contents/breast-pain\u003E","Brennan M, Houssami N, French J. Management of benign breast conditions [Internet]. racgp.org.au. 2005 [cited 18 August 2021]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afpbackissues/2005/200503/200503brennan.pdf","Cornell, L.F., Sandhu, N.P., Pruthi, S., Mussallem, D.M., 2020. Current Management and Treatment Options for Breast Pain. Mayo Clinic Proceedings 95, 574\u2013580.. doi:10.1016/j.mayocp.2019.12.014","Hubbard TJ, Sharma A, Ferguson DJ. Breast pain: assessment, management, and referral criteria. British journal of general practice. 2020;70(697):419\u201320. Available online: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7384817/","Hafiz Shazia P., Barnes Nicola L. P., Kirwan Cliona C. (2018) Clinical management of idiopathic mastalgia: a systematic review. Journal of Primary Health Care 10, 312-323. Available online: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31039960/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32186"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1197"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32186"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-23T21:21:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-23T21:21:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1197"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47470"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":